### Pools <span style="color:#ff9800;font-weight:600;">(WIP — advanced)</span>

> <strong>Work in progress — array is still the primary product path.</strong><br>
> <strong>Fine to use now:</strong> set your own free-space Warning/Critical (disk sizes or custom), Main coloring (solid/outline), and Unraid <strong>alerts</strong> for pools. Thresholds are plain free-space checks; they work for alerting and color changes.<br>
> <strong>Not there yet:</strong> BTRFS “math” / profile-aware suggested thresholds (e.g. auto headroom by RAID1 vs RAID5/6 vs RAID10). Notification <em>wording</em> already adapts by profile class; recommended numbers do not.<br>
> Defaults leave pools inactive (thresholds None, pool alerts off) until you configure them here.

Pool names come from your server. Unraid often defaults the first pool to <strong>cache</strong>, but every pool—including the first—can be named however you like.

Defaults for pool thresholds are <strong>None</strong> (opt-in).

<blockquote class="inline_help">
<strong>RAID1 / multi-mirror:</strong> losing one disk usually still leaves your data on remaining copies—free space is more about rebuild/rebalance after replace, not “evacuate like the array.”<br>
<strong>RAID5/6:</strong> free space is closer to recovery headroom after a failure (rebalance/replace).<br>
<strong>RAID10:</strong> one failure often OK for data; restoring full redundancy may need free space.<br>
<strong>single/RAID0:</strong> free thresholds are capacity policy only—disk loss risks data.
</blockquote>

